'''Glenda Hall''' (born 5 May 1964 in [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]]) is an [[Australians|Australian]] former [[cricket]] player.<ref name="ESPNcricinfo - Glenda Hall - Australia">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/53506.html|title=Glenda Hall - Australia|work=[[ESPNcricinfo]]|publisher=[[ESPN Inc.]]|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> Hall played two [[Women's Test cricket|tests]] and two [[Women's One Day International cricket|one day internationals]] for the [[Australia national women's cricket team]].<ref name="ESPNcricinfo - Glenda Hall - Australia"/>

In 1985 Hall was a member of an Australian "[[Board President's XI (Australia)|Board President's XI]]" along with players including [[Marie Cornish]], [[Tina Macpherson]], [[Karen Brown (cricketer)|Karen Brown]] and [[Trish Dawson]] that played against a [[Women's Cricket Association]] XI selected by [[Audrey Collins]].<ref name="The Age - 9 January 1985 - Hawke might go into bat for women">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1300&dat=19850109&id=hzlVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=kJUDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2542,2713823|title=Hawke might go into bat for women|last=[[Peg McMahon]]|date=9 January 1985|work=[[The Age]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>

On 5 April 2019, Hall was one of the first six inductees into the Cricket ACT Hall of Fame.  The other five were [[Peter Solway]], [[Michael Bevan]], [[Bronwyn Calver]], [[Lorne Lees]] and [[Greg Irvine]].<ref name="The Canberra Times - 5 April 2019 - Ethan Bartlett and Cherie Taylor claim Cricket ACT's top crowns">{{cite news|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6004831/ethan-bartlett-and-cherie-taylor-claim-cricket-acts-top-crowns/|title=Ethan Bartlett and Cherie Taylor claim Cricket ACT's top crowns|last=Helmers|first=Caden|date=5 April 2019|work=[[The Canberra Times]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=9 April 2019}}</ref>
